

                                  SPECIAL PERMISSIONS WITH SETUID,SETGID AND STICKY BIT
                                 <------------------------------------------------------>

--> All permissions on a file or directory are referred as bits

     -rwx        rwx       rwx -------> every letter is a bit
       |          |         |
       |          |         |
     Users     Groups   Others

NOTE:- To change this permissions we use chmod command
                                        -------

--> There are 3 additionals permissions in linux
      1.setuid:bits telss linux to run a program with the effective user id of the owner instead of the executor.(e.g.passwd command) 
        /etc/shadow
   
      2.bit telss linux to run a program with the effective group id of the owner instead of the executor.(e.g.locate or wall command)
          Please Note:This bit is present for only files which have executable permissions

      3.sticky bit: a bit set on files/directories that allows only the owner or root to delete those files.

--> To assign special permissions at the user level

    1.chmod u+s xyz.sh

--> To assign special permissions at the group level
 
    1.chmod g+s xyz.sh

--> To remove special permissions at the user or group level

    1.chmod u-s xyz.sh
    2.chmod g-s xyz.sh

--> To find all executables in Linux with setuid and setgid permissions
    
      1.find / -perm /6000 -type f 

--> Sticky bit

    1.It is assigned to the last bit of permissions

         -rwx rwx rwt   ---> here t is assigned for security that user can't delete the directory       EX:- /tmp directory

                SYNTAX:- chmod +t directoryname

Plesase Note:- This bits work on C programming executables not on bash shell scripts..




                                                 

